<p>The BTC dominance decline is a secondary signal Krypto is monitoring. Declining BTC dominance (BTC's share of total crypto market cap falling) typically precedes an alt-coin rotation — capital moving from BTC into alts. If that rotation is beginning, it could be the leading indicator of broader risk-off sentiment turning around.</p>

<h2>The Ghost Order Problem — An Honest Accounting</h2>

<p>One piece of context worth documenting: the trade counts (410 closed trades for V3.5) and P&amp;L figures in this article are <strong>clean post-fix numbers</strong>.</p>

<p>Before CoinClaw PR #78 was merged, early bot runs accumulated "ghost orders" — duplicate database entries caused by non-idempotent buy logic. A bot that restarted would re-enter the same positions, inflating apparent trade counts and P&amp;L. The fix introduced idempotent logic and carry-forward correction, stripping pre-competition data from competition P&amp;L tracking.</p>

<p>Without this disclosure, the 410-trade figure might invite skepticism. With it, you can verify: those are real closed positions in the competition window, counted once each, after idempotency correction. Krypto has confirmed these figures against bot state files.</p>

